Identify offline privacy risks and protections

In this activity, I explored some offline privacy risks in my daily environment and how they can be mitigated.

1. Shoulder surfing  
When using my phone or laptop in public places like UniHall or campus, other people may see my screen. This can expose sensitive information such as passwords or personal messages. To reduce this risk, I try to position my screen away from others or lower the brightness.

2. Lost or stolen student card  
If my UWA student card is lost, someone could use it to access buildings or facilities. To prevent this, I keep my card secure and report it immediately if lost.

3. Visible personal information  
Documents or screens showing personal information can be seen by others. I avoid leaving sensitive information open in public areas.

4. Physical access to my room  
If I leave my room unlocked, someone could enter without permission. I always lock my door when leaving and use my keycard securely.

5. Being recorded by CCTV  
Although CCTV improves security, it also means my movements can be recorded. This raises privacy concerns about how data is stored and used.

Overall, offline privacy risks are common in everyday life, and simple habits can help reduce exposure of personal information.
